525. Contiguous Array
Problem

Given a binary array nums, return the maximum length of a contiguous subarray with an equal number of 0s and 1s.

Example 1
Input: nums = [0,1]

Output: 2
Example 2
Input: nums = [0,1,0]

Output: 2
Approach 1: Brute Force
Intuition

Check every possible subarray.

Count the number of 0s and 1s.

If they are equal, update the maximum length.

Java
class Solution {
    public int findMaxLength(int[] nums) {

        int maxLen = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            int zeros = 0;
            int ones = 0;

            for (int j = i; j < nums.length; j++) {

                if (nums[j] == 0)
                    zeros++;
                else
                    ones++;

                if (zeros == ones) {
                    maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, j - i + 1);
                }
            }
        }

        return maxLen;
    }
}

Complexity
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)
Approach 2: Prefix Sum + HashMap (Optimal)
Key Observation

Convert:

0 → -1
1 → +1

Now if a subarray has equal numbers of 0s and 1s:

Sum = 0

More generally:

If the same prefix sum appears again,

prefixSum(i) = prefixSum(j)

then the subarray between them has sum 0.

Thus it contains equal numbers of 0s and 1s.

Intuition

Store:

Prefix Sum → First Index

Whenever the same sum appears again:

Length = CurrentIndex - FirstOccurrenceIndex

Update maximum length.

Java
class Solution {
    public int findMaxLength(int[] nums) {

        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        map.put(0, -1);

        int sum = 0;
        int maxLen = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            if (nums[i] == 0)
                sum += -1;
            else
                sum += 1;

            if (map.containsKey(sum)) {

                maxLen = Math.max(
                        maxLen,
                        i - map.get(sum)
                );

            } else {

                map.put(sum, i);
            }
        }

        return maxLen;
    }
}
